                     <interp inst="t18280911-349-off1797" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-349-off1797" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18280911-349-cd1798" type="crimeDate">1st of July</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-349-off1797 t18280911-349-cd1798"></join>, 3 blankets, value 4s.; 2 sheets, value 3s.; and 1 bed, value 3l.
            </rs>; the goods of 
               <persName id="t18280911-349-victim1895" type="victimName">
                  Elizabeth 
                  Robinson
               <interp inst="t18280911-349-victim1895" type="surname" value="Robinson"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-349-victim1895" type="given" value="Elizabeth"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-349-victim1895" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-349-off1797 t18280911-349-victim1895"></join>
                  </persName>
            , <rs id="t18280911-349-viclabel1799" type="occupation">widow</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-349-victim1895 t18280911-349-viclabel1799"></join>.</p>
               <p>ELIZABETH ROBINSON. I am a widow, and live in <placeName id="t18280911-349-crimeloc1800">Cartwright-square</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280911-349-crimeloc1800" type="placeName" value="Cartwright-square"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280911-349-crimeloc1800" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-349-off1797 t18280911-349-crimeloc1800"></join> near the London-docks; the prisoner lodged at my house about four years - he left me on the 1st of July, but did not tell me he was going; he locked the door of his room. On the 4th of July, I got an officer and opened the door; these articles were all gone, and there was nothing worth mentioning left - they had been let as part of the furniture of the lodging; the prisoner appeared to be married - there was a woman with him; he came back on the 4th of July, and abused me for opening the door.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. BODKIN. Q. Had you not taken some spirits that day? A. No, there was no abuse on my side; he said, he had taken the bed, and I might do my worst.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-349-person1896">
                  ELIZABETH 
                  ROBINSON
               <interp inst="t18280911-349-person1896" type="surname" value="ROBINSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-349-person1896" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-349-person1896" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the prosecutrix's daughter. On the 4th of July, we sent for an officer, and got the door open; the prisoner sent his sister-in-law, and then he came himself - he told my mother he had taken her bed and she might do her worst.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Did you not find the key of his door hanging outside? A. No, the officer drew the staple out: the bed has not been found.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-349-person1897">
                  JAMES 
                  ROBERTS
               <interp inst="t18280911-349-person1897" type="surname" value="ROBERTS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-349-person1897" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-349-person1897" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I took the prisoner - he asked me what I wanted with him; I said for taking a feather bed and other articles from Mrs. Robinson - he denied it, but when he saw her, he said, he was willing to settle the matter; I questioned him about the bed - he said, it was made away with; he offered to pay Mrs Robinson 4s. a week.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280911-349-verdict1801" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18280911-349-verdict1801" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 30.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280911-349-punish1802" type="punishmentDescription">
